# Let and Const ğŸ›¡ï¸

As learned in Basics, replace `var` with `let` and `const`.

- **Block Scope:** Variables are only accessible inside the `{ block }` they are defined in.
- **No Hoisting:** You cannot use them before declaration.

```javascript
if (true) {
  let x = 10;
}
// console.log(x); // Error! x is not defined
```

# Spread Operator (...) ğŸ§‚

Expands an iterable (like an array) into more elements.

## Combine Arrays
```javascript
const arr1 = [1, 2];
const arr2 = [3, 4];
const combined = [...arr1, ...arr2]; // [1, 2, 3, 4]
```

## Object Copy
```javascript
const obj1 = { x: 1, y: 2 };
const obj2 = { ...obj1, z: 3 };
```

# Classes ğŸ›ï¸

Syntactic sugar over JavaScript's existing prototype-based inheritance.

```javascript
class Car {
  constructor(brand) {
    this.carname = brand;
  }
  present() {
    return "I have a " + this.carname;
  }
}

const myCar = new Car("Ford");
myCar.present();
```

# Class Inheritance ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ‘¦

Use the `extends` keyword to create a child class.

```javascript
class Model extends Car {
  constructor(brand, mod) {
    super(brand); // Call parent constructor
    this.model = mod;
  }
  show() {
    return this.present() + ", it is a " + this.model;
  }
}
```

# Modules ğŸ“¦

Modules allow you to break up your code into separate files.

## Export (lib.js)
```javascript
export const pi = 3.14;
export function add(x, y) { return x + y; }
```

## Import (main.js)
```javascript
import { pi, add } from './lib.js';
console.log(add(1, 2));
```
Note: Requires `type="module"` in HTML script tag.

# Map and Set ğŸ—ºï¸

## Map
A collection of keyed data items, like an Object. But keys can be of **any** type.
```javascript
const map = new Map();
map.set('1', 'str1');
map.set(1, 'num1');
```

## Set
A collection of **unique** values.
```javascript
const set = new Set([1, 2, 2, 3]);
console.log(set); // {1, 2, 3}
```
